[2] West Virginia
Date: Fri 31 Aug 2018
Source: West Virginia Department of Health & Human Resources, Office of Epidemiology & Prevention Services [edited]
https://dhhr.wv.gov/oeps/disease/viral-hepatitis/Pages/hepA_outbreak.aspx


Since March 2018, the West Virginia Bureau for Public Health has reported an increase in the number of confirmed cases of acute hepatitis A virus. This increase in cases has primarily been among injection and non-injection drug users, homeless or mobile individuals, and those who have been recently incarcerated. Viral sequencing has linked cases from Kentucky and California.

West Virginia hepatitis A outbreak cases as of 31 Aug 2018
---------------------------
Number of cases 1109

Demographics
Age range: 12-82
Median age: 37
Male: 666 (60.1 percent)
Hospitalizations: 588 (53 percent)
Deaths: 2

Risk factors
Co-infection with hepatitis C (information available for 951 cases): 584 (61.4 percent)
Co-infection with hepatitis B (information available for 951 cases): 108 (11.4 percent)
Reports illicit drug use (information available for 928 cases): 727 (78.3 percent)
Homeless: 132 (11.9 percent)

