[Date / Cases / New cases per week
23 May 2018 / 106
29 Jun 2018 / 404 / 59
13 Jul 2018 / 540 / 68
27 Jul 2018 / 699 / 79
24 Aug 2018 / 1031 / 83
31 Aug 2018 / 1109 / 78

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of West Virginia, United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6012457,249

These are weekly numbers similar to what is currently occurring in Kentucky. West Virginia has passed California and Michigan for 2nd on the HAV case number list. With the 1031 number in West Virginia and Kentucky's 1425, these 2 states have reported 2456 cases. In the entire year of 2016 (https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/statistics/2016surveillance/index.htm), CDC reported only 2007 cases from all 50 states.

Those affected the most are the marginalized cohorts of humanity, including homeless people and substance abusers. Their needs for adequate sanitation and living conditions were supplied in the San Diego (CA) area, and such an approach to these outbreaks is required elsewhere in the USA. Spill-over into other portions of the population, such as restaurant diners affected through infected food handlers, will continue. It is not clear how many of these rapidly increasing cases are in individuals outside the described cohorts.

Kentucky remains in 1st place in cases. West Virginia has roared passed California and Michigan for 2nd on the HAV case number list. With the 1109 number in West Virginia and Kentucky's 1572, these 2 states have reported 2681 cases. In the entire year of 2016 (https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/statistics/2016surveillance/index.htm), CDC reported only 2007 cases from all 50 states. Based on weekly numbers, there is no sign of decreasing numbers. It is not entirely clear what public-health responses are occurring in these two states. - Mod.LL]
